&lt;h1 id="navigating-cities-and-understanding-proofs"&gt;Navigating Cities and Understanding Proofs&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;How proofs are like cities&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://i0.wp.com/rjlipton.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/images.jpeg?ssl=1"&gt;&lt;img src="https://i0.wp.com/rjlipton.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/images.jpeg?w=150&amp;amp;ssl=1" alt="" title="images"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Pierre L’Enfant was not a theorist, but a designer, and in particular the designer of the physical layout of Washington D.C.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Today I want to talk about why some proofs are hard to understand, not hard to discover.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>